.TH APACTION 3 
.SH NAME
ap_reg, ap_ureg \- register and unregister anticipation point entries
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include <stdint.h>
#include <ap.h>


int ap_reg(uintptr_t \fIap_addr\fP, void(*) (uint8_t) *\fIap_handler\fP, uint8_t \fIap_flags\fP);
int ap_ureg(uintptr_t \fIap_addr\fP, void(*) (uint8_t) *\fIap_handler\fP);
int ap_sret(uintptr_t \fIr_addr\fP);

.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fBap_reg\fR() and \fBap_ureg\fR() functions allow the caller to
register and unregister anticipation point handlers to specific
instruction addresses. The argument \fIap_addr\fR specifies the
instruction address that will be preempted by the anticipation point
handler. Registering an anticipation entry will result in execution
transfering to the associated \fIap_handler\fP when the program counter
reaches the \fIap_addr\fP.

An entry is uniquely identified by the pair of \fIap_addr\fP and
\fIap_handler\fP. To register or unregister both must be provided, passing
a \fINULL\fP value for \fIap_handler\fP will result in undefined
behavior. Multiple handlers may be registered to the same address, 
the order in which they are executed when triggered is
non-deterministic. Subsequent registrations of an entry is equivalent
to replacing the already registered entry, which may be desireable to
change the flags on an entry.

The default behavior when returning from an \fIap_handler\fP is to
resume execution at the \fIap_addr\fP. The return behavior may be 
modified by returning using \fIap_sret\fP. The \fIap_sret\fP call 
sets the return address of a \fIap_handler\fP to \fIr_addr\fP. 
Note, the stack contents and stack pointer will be restored to the
values present when execution was anticipated at \fIap_addr\fP. 

When returning from an \fIap_handler\fP, you must use the APRET macro,
as this ensures that the program is restored to the correct state. Returning
without the APRET macro, either via return or exiting the handler's scope, will result in undefined behavior.

.SH FLAGS

\fIap_flags\fP modifies the behavior of a registered entry. It is
formed by the bitwise OR of zero or more of the following:

.B AP_DISABLE
If
.I ap_flags
is
.BR AP_DISABLE
then the entry is disabled and will not be anticipated.

.B AP_ONESHOT
If
.I ap_flags
is
.BR AP_ONESHOT
then the execution is allowed to continue after returning from the \fIap_handler\fP, and will only anticipate if it encounters the trigger address (e.g if the trigger address is inside a loop). If this flag is not set, execution will be immediately antticipated again after returning from the \fIap_handler\fP.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, \fBap_reg\fR() and \fBap_ureg\fR() return 0.
On error, \-1 is returned 
.SH ERRORS
On error, these functions set errno to indicate the cause of the failure. Possible error values include:

.TP
.B EINVAL
ap_flags contains bits other than AP_DISABLE or AP_ONESHOT (or their valid combinations), or ap_addr or r_addr is not a valid instruction address, or ap_handler is Null, or ap_addr equals 0.
.TP
.B ENOMEM
No hardware breakpoints left to register the anticipation point entry.
.TP

.SH EXAMPLES
An example demonstrating the use of these functions:
.PP
.nf
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <errno.h>
#include "ap.h"



void my_fn_handler(uintptr_t addr) {
  uintptr_t new_addr = 0xdeadbeef; 
  printf("Handler called for address: 0x%lx\n", addr);
  //...
  ap_sret(new_addr);
  APRET(0, 0);
}

int main() {
  uintptr_t instr_addr = 0x12345678; // Example instruction address
  uint8_t flags = AP_ONESHOT; //enable the AP_ONESHOT flag
  if(ap_reg(instr_addr, my_fn_handler, flags) == -1) {
    switch (errno) {
      case EINVAL:
        printf("Invalid arguments provided to ap_reg.\n");
        break;
      case ENOMEM:
        printf("No more AP entries available.\n");
        break;
      default:
        printf("An unknown error occurred: %d\n", errno);
    }
  }

  ap_ureg(instr_addr, my_fn_handler); 
  return 0;
}
.fi
